Great â€” if everyone in your team needs access to the Kubernetes Dashboard, you should not give the entire cluster full unrestricted admin access.
Instead, you should set up a secure RBAC access model that matches how you already run your banking microservices (multiple namespaces like springboot-bau, springboot-migration, etc.).

Below is a safe and professional setup used in enterprise on-prem Kubernetes clusters.

â¸»

âœ… Goal

All team members should be able to see:

âœ” Their namespaces
âœ” Pods, logs, events
âœ” Deployments, ReplicaSets
âœ” Services, ConfigMaps, Secrets (optional)
âœ” Nodes (read-only)
âœ” Dashboard graphs

But team members should NOT be able to:

âœ˜ Modify cluster-wide configuration
âœ˜ Delete system pods
âœ˜ Modify kube-system
âœ˜ Touch other teamsâ€™ namespaces
âœ˜ Modify cluster networking, Calico, CNI, etc.

â¸»

â­ Recommended Setup: RBAC Role for Team-Wide Access

We will configure:
	1.	One shared ServiceAccount named team-dashboard-user
	2.	One ClusterRole (read-only for cluster resources, full access for your namespaces)
	3.	One RoleBinding per namespace
	4.	A small ClusterRoleBinding that allows read-only views across cluster components

This gives a perfect balance between visibility and safety.

â¸»

ğŸ“Œ STEP 1 â€” Create the Service Account

vi dashboard-team-sa.yaml

Paste this:

apiVersion: v1
kind: ServiceAccount
metadata:
  name: team-dashboard-user
  namespace: kubernetes-dashboard

Apply it:

kubectl apply -f dashboard-team-sa.yaml


â¸»

ğŸ“Œ STEP 2 â€” Create Team Role (Full Access to Team Namespaces)

Create:

vi team-ns-role.yaml

Paste:

apiVersion: rbac.authorization.k8s.io/v1
kind: Role
metadata:
  name: namespace-admin
rules:
  - apiGroups: ["", "apps", "batch"]
    resources: ["pods", "pods/log", "pods/exec", "deployments", "replicasets", "services", "configmaps", "secrets", "jobs"]
    verbs: ["get", "watch", "list", "create", "update", "patch", "delete"]

Apply:

kubectl apply -f team-ns-role.yaml -n springboot-bau
kubectl apply -f team-ns-role.yaml -n springboot-migration
# (add all your namespaces here)


â¸»

ğŸ“Œ STEP 3 â€” Bind Role to ServiceAccount

For each namespace:

kubectl create rolebinding ns-admin-binding \
  --role=namespace-admin \
  --serviceaccount=kubernetes-dashboard:team-dashboard-user \
  -n springboot-bau

Then:

kubectl create rolebinding ns-admin-binding \
  --role=namespace-admin \
  --serviceaccount=kubernetes-dashboard:team-dashboard-user \
  -n springboot-migration

Repeat for all namespaces.

â¸»

ğŸ“Œ STEP 4 â€” Read-Only Access to Cluster Info (nodes, storage, events)

Create:

vi dashboard-readonly-clusterrole.yaml

Paste:

apiVersion: rbac.authorization.k8s.io/v1
kind: ClusterRole
metadata:
  name: dashboard-readonly-cluster
rules:
  - apiGroups: [""]
    resources: ["nodes", "namespaces"]
    verbs: ["get", "list", "watch"]
  - apiGroups: ["metrics.k8s.io"]
    resources: ["pods", "nodes"]
    verbs: ["get", "list", "watch"]

Apply:

kubectl apply -f dashboard-readonly-clusterrole.yaml

Bind it:

kubectl create clusterrolebinding dashboard-readonly-binding \
  --clusterrole=dashboard-readonly-cluster \
  --serviceaccount=kubernetes-dashboard:team-dashboard-user


â¸»

ğŸ“Œ STEP 5 â€” Generate Token for Team Access

kubectl -n kubernetes-dashboard create token team-dashboard-user

Share this token with your team.

Anyone can use this same token.

â¸»

ğŸ‰ TEAM DASHBOARD IS READY

Your team will now see:

âœ” All pods/logs in allowed namespaces

âœ” All deployments & services

âœ” Node status (read-only)

âœ” Events, metrics, graphs

âœ” CronJobs, Jobs, ReplicaSets

But they cannot:

âœ˜ Modify kube-system
âœ˜ Edit Calico
âœ˜ Touch control-plane
âœ˜ Break networking
âœ˜ Delete system components

This is exactly how enterprise banking workloads configure dashboard access.

